## 1. Guiding Principles

**One seam at a time.**  
Never migrate the whole algorithm at once. Move one module — e.g., evaluation — wrap it in a `cudaMemcpy` bridge, verify correctness against the CPU oracle, measure, then move forward. Skipping this discipline makes CUDA race conditions and memory faults nearly impossible to isolate.

**Measure before optimizing.**  
Every phase produces a profiling report before any optimization is applied. If you cannot point to a specific metric (load efficiency, occupancy, bank conflicts, transfer time) that is bad, you do not have a reason to optimize.

**Memory over compute.**  
GPUs are memory-bound. An optimization that does more arithmetic but reads less from global memory is almost always a net win. The roofline model applies: identify whether each kernel is compute-bound or memory-bound before choosing an optimization strategy.

**The CPU oracle is permanent.**  
The Phase 10 serial baseline remains the correctness reference for every GPU phase. No GPU result is accepted unless its tour lengths and fitness values match the CPU baseline within documented tolerance on the fixed-seed regression suite.

**Prefer algorithmic upgrades over micro-optimizations.**  
A hybrid GA + 2-opt memetic approach will outperform a heavily tuned pure GA on solution quality. Do not spend three sprints on warp shuffles if the algorithm is structurally weak.

