## 11. Phase 16 — GPU 2-Opt Local Search

**Goal:** Introduce a memetic component. This is the phase where the solver transitions from "fast GA" to "competitive TSP solver."

### The Algorithmic Case for 2-Opt

A standard GA generates diverse candidate tours but converges slowly on solution quality because crossover alone does not exploit local structure. The TSP literature is unambiguous: **local search is where quality lives**. LKH's dominance over pure evolutionary approaches is built on aggressive k-opt moves, not evolutionary operators.

The GPU's strength is evaluating massive numbers of independent move candidates simultaneously — exactly what 2-opt requires. This is where GPU and algorithm reinforce each other naturally.

### 2-Opt on GPU: Block-Collaborative Design

Do **not** assign one thread per edge swap — the sequential search for the best improving move is too slow. Assign **one thread block per tour**: all threads in the block cooperatively evaluate all $O(n^2)$ candidate swaps, perform a parallel reduction to find the best improving swap, and apply it.

```
For tour i, one block of T threads:
  Thread t evaluates edges (t, t+1), (t + T, t + T + 1), ...
  (strided across the n*(n-1)/2 candidate pairs)
  → parallel reduction within block: find best delta
  → if best delta < 0: apply the swap (single thread writes)
  → repeat until no improving move found (or iteration limit)
```

```cuda
__global__ void two_opt_block(
        int *d_cities, double *d_lengths,
        const double *d_dist, int n, int N,
        int max_iters)
{
    /* One block per tour */
    int tour_id = blockIdx.x;
    if (tour_id >= N) return;

    extern __shared__ double s_delta[];   /* one entry per thread */

    int *tour = d_cities + tour_id;       /* SoA: stride N between genes */

    for (int iter = 0; iter < max_iters; iter++) {
        double best_delta = 0.0;
        int best_i = -1, best_j = -1;

        /* Strided sweep of all (i, j) pairs */
        int total_pairs = (n * (n - 1)) / 2;
        for (int p = threadIdx.x; p < total_pairs; p += blockDim.x) {
            /* Decode pair (i, j) from linear index p */
            int i = /* ... */ , j = /* ... */;
            double delta = /* 2-opt delta for (i, j) */;
            if (delta < best_delta) { best_delta = delta; best_i = i; best_j = j; }
        }

        /* Block reduction: find global best */
        s_delta[threadIdx.x] = best_delta;
        __syncthreads();
        for (int stride = blockDim.x / 2; stride > 0; stride >>= 1) {
            if (threadIdx.x < stride && s_delta[threadIdx.x + stride] < s_delta[threadIdx.x])
                s_delta[threadIdx.x] = s_delta[threadIdx.x + stride];
            __syncthreads();
        }

        if (s_delta[0] >= 0.0) break;   /* no improvement: converged */

        /* Thread 0 applies the best swap */
        if (threadIdx.x == 0 && best_i >= 0)
            /* reverse segment [i+1 .. j] in tour */;
        __syncthreads();
    }
}
```

### Integration into the GA Loop

Apply 2-opt every $K$ generations (not every generation) to control overhead. A good default is $K = 10$ with a per-call iteration limit of 3–5 passes.

```
GA loop:
  every generation: select → crossover → mutate → evaluate
  every K generations: 2-opt local search on all individuals → re-evaluate
```

