## 14. Testing Strategy

For every GPU phase, four test classes are required. No phase gate waives any class.

### A — Exact Equivalence Tests

Used for deterministic operators (evaluation, fixed-input crossover, fixed-input mutation). CPU and GPU outputs must match within tolerance.

```bash
# Example: verify evaluation kernel
./tests/test_evaluate_gpu --instance square_4.tsp --pop 16 --seed 42
# Expected: all 16 tour lengths within 1e-9 of CPU reference
```

### B — Invariant Tests

These do not require exact value matches; they enforce structural correctness.

| Invariant | Required |
|-----------|----------|
| Every tour is a valid permutation | After every crossover, mutation, 2-opt call |
| Population size is constant | After every generation |
| Best-so-far is non-increasing under elitism | Across all generations |
| No NaN or Inf in fitness array | After every evaluation |

```bash
compute-sanitizer --tool memcheck ./ga_cuda_debug \
    --instance medium_500.tsp --pop 512 --gen 200 --seed 42
# Required: zero out-of-bounds accesses
```

### C — Statistical Tests

For operators where exact equivalence with serial is not achievable (different RNG).

| Test | Criterion |
|------|-----------|
| Selection pressure | Best individual wins > 85% of 10,000 tournaments (k=2) |
| Mutation frequency | At `p_m = 0.5`, 45%–55% of tours change per generation |
| Population diversity | Shannon entropy of fitness does not collapse before gen 100 |

### D — Performance Regression Tests

An optimization that doesn't improve a measurable metric is not accepted.

| Phase | Required Improvement |
|-------|---------------------|
| 12 | Transfer time < 10% of total (was > 60%) |
| 13 | Global load efficiency > 80% (was < 20%) |
| 15 | DRAM read bytes reduced vs Phase 13 |
| 16 | Best tour quality improves vs Phase 14 at matched time |
| 17 | Kernel count per generation reduced vs Phase 16 |

