## 16. Literature Reference Points

These provide context for where your implementation should sit relative to the state of the art.

| Reference | Relevance |
|-----------|-----------|
| TSP_GPU v2.3 (Burtscher & Pingali, Texas State) | GPU-accelerated 2-opt hill climbing; benchmark for local search throughput |
| Molina et al., PDPTA 2011 — *A Parallel GPU Version of the TSP* | CUDA GA + 2-opt hybridization; directly analogous architecture |
| Helsgaun — *General k-opt submoves for Lin–Kernighan* | CPU quality reference; LKH is the standard TSP heuristic baseline |
| Burtscher et al., GPGPU 2015 — *Rethinking Parallelization of Hill Climbing* | Memory access and warp divergence analysis for GPU local search |

**How to use these:** do not benchmark against LKH as if you expect to win on solution quality — LKH uses decades of TSP-specific engineering. Use it as an **optimality gap reference**: report how far your best solution is from LKH's solution, not whether you beat it.

For GPU-to-GPU comparisons, TSP_GPU v2.3 is the honest target. Reproducing a fraction of its throughput on 2-opt move evaluation is a meaningful result.

